caption: Small serving sizes, not very much injera for the amount of food, poor customer service (waiter kept smirking when we were complaining), forgets to put in part of our order, and tells us they only accept cash after we finish our meal. My water cup tasted like it wasn’t properly cleaned (could taste spiced tea residue). Lukewarm water.(big thumbs down)
Delicious!! Full Vegan menu😍
Food was great but the service was slow due to only one waiter.

It was okayish. Quite hot inside even though it was very cool outside. No more meat on the menu anymore and not sure why the change. The mushroom stew was tasty, but the other dish we ordered was bland even though it was billed as spicy. Lukewarm water.
Delicious with really good service. Support them especially during covid!
They don’t know how to make enjera, they will give you something that looks like enjera but actually is not. It took them more than 30mins to give us water, and the food was disgusting.
Sambussas and veggie platter. So much flavor, loved it!
The peanut milk is die to for. Service and everything else was okay.
Fast service and really good vegan food!
Great place to eat for vegetarian options
Food was amazing, fresh and good portion and get that vegetarian combo plate
Its vegan only now
Tasty. Friendly service. BYOB
Excellent.
Love this place. Very good food and friendly service. A bit pricey for the portions, but delicious vegan food
Delicious food that smells amazing. I'm not a vegetarian and they don't serve liquor. Still, it's worth going.
This is a beautiful restaurant. The food was amazing and I will definitely be returning!

I thought originally this place served mears, but it us a vegetarian/vegan( this was my mistzke). The lentils, potatoes. Etc, tasted great. This is from someone who eats 99%meat, and I would never be vegetarian, let alone Vegan. Taste was very good, I'm only giving 4 stars though because we need more bread with the dishes, or maybe cutlery, as I finished 2 servings of bread and we still had half a plate to go down. Abd you need to order more bread to finish, but it also makes it more expensive! The service was excellent!
Awesome food!

We got the Ethiopian Love Veggie Sampler and it was delicious! I also recommend the Ethiopian style iced tea. Even the water was good tasting. Service was great and the environment in the restaurant was relaxed and comfortable.

One of my first stops on the island and a joy to experience every time. The food is an adventure of spices and care. I love the vegan options, and enjoy sharing my favorite wots with friends and family. The food is what you'll go for, but the experience will keep EL on your mind.

Food was awesome, service was super friendly. Couple things to note, just to set expectations: They're no longer doing outdoor patio seating, and the menu is now completely vegan. That said, they still have a lot of options & good portions.

Love this spot! The food is always more than excellent. The owners take great pride in creating top notch food over the years. I would say this is my favorite restaurant in Hawaii. What I also enjoy is that they have so many yummy vegan options! I eat meat but love all their platters. My favorite is Awaze Wot and the vegetarian platter! Also even with many allergies I can eat all their food which makes me even happier! Thank you :)

We got the veggie sampler for two (for $42). The food was ok (yet not authentic, especially the injera) but the portions were so small that we were both still hungry afterwards. They also only give you two small rolls of injera, which is not enough to actually eat the meal with your hands (even though there isn't much food on the plate to begin with). They offered to bring more injera and then charged us for it! I didn't believe the other negative reviews when I first read them and thought people were just complaining but after eating there, I do not recommend this place.
Food is amazing!! Beautiful atmosphere

My boyfriend surprised me with a date night to this restaurant ( he also knew I had been craving Ethiopian food since we left the mainland, Oregon). I have to say I was quite disappointed. First, they had small portions. Especially when the prices were so high. Second, the waiter was quite shocked how fast we finished our meal and offered red lentils and some other non filling food “on the house.” Third, we didn’t receive napkins until the end of our meal. Fourth, we showed up 10 minutes after they opened and the tables weren’t setup. Fifth, we didn’t received refills on our water. When we were leaving, the waiter asked my boyfriend how was it, my boyfriend told him it was good only to save him from embarrassment.

Worst "Ethiopian" food I've ever had in my life. Tonight was my second chance eating. The first time was 9 month ago when I first arrived on island. It was bad then and worse now. If you have ever had Ethiopian food dont eat here, you'll be severely disappointed. The food is tasteless slop. Literally. I got the beef ribs and lamb tibs... get this its ground, not a single chunk of meat in sight. No peppers, no onion, no tomato. Nothing. Injera was the inky thing that tasted even a bit authentic and even that was barely. I wish I could give this place zero stars.
Great food and friendly customer service. We had to ask for more injera and we got more freshly baked ones.. Glad they were open for dining in after COVID closures.
This restaurant showed me how much I love Ethiopian food.

Always fantastic food. Some of the best Ethiopian food I've ever had -- and I've eaten at Ethiopian restaurants in DC, NYC, SF, and Seattle -- what a surprise to discover that the best of them all is in Honolulu! Don't miss the vegetarian love platter and the sambusas -- the perfect amount of spicy goodness! *ask for their house hot sauce or hot powder if you really like it spicy!
First experience with Ethiopian food. I was pleasantly surprised with the burst of flavors that was in the Ethiopian Love Veggie Sampler. I love the injera bread. Highly recommend these place.
We have been here multiple times. The food is amazing and has great flavor. Definitely the best Ethiopian food I’ve tasted since visiting Ethiopia.

Holy cow!  This was a really great meal!  This Chinatown restaurant was nicely decorated, very clean, and perfect for a data.  The menu had plenty of options for a variety of tastes, and the food was extremely tasty.  The wait staff was a little laid back.  If I needed something, I had to get their attention, but I appreciated that they weren't interrupting my conversation.  10/10 will go back.
Food is delicious but injera is small and not the traditional one and also pricey for the portion. But all in all good food. The place is also clean and modern.
Amazing food, and a really nice environment. So flavorful, definitely will be coming again.
I've never had Ethiopian food except for here, so I can't speak to it's authenticity or anything like that, but it is delicious!
Love the food.   Always good.   Great place to take a small group of friends and eat family style.
Great food!  Nice atmosphere. Parking sucks a little. But assumed it would, due to location.
First experience eating Ethiopian food and it was delicious service was genuinely authentic, Aunty Mekey hooked us up and answered every question! Definitely coming back.

It is with a heavy heart I write this review!!! Not Authentic Ethiopian food! Tomato Salad had spoiled tomatoes! Enjera so horrible. Location not bad but no ceiling fans so hot inside at 7:30 pm. So sad for me I thought I had a place special for me in Honolulu 12/23/19. I didn't read the reviews before I went but 1 star said same thy not euthentic to pricey small tasteless portions

One of my favorite restaurants. I always get the veggie sampler with our choice of 2 meat dishes. Try Sambusa and Ethiopian ice tea to start, and if you have room, the baklava for desert. So good!! Fair warning you'll be eating with your hands.
Casual place with excellent food.
Food was “ok” but I could’ve walked to Ethiopia and back while waiting for the check
Super good food and hella chill vibe! Bring your own wine and relax with good company! Great for small groups.

(Translated by Google) I liked it, but Ethiopian bread is like acid and the food is very spicy. I would only go back for the peanut honey tea  (Original) Me gustó, pero el pan etíope es como ácido y la comida toda muy picante. Sólo volvería a por el peanut honey tea
Was out here from London and was surprised, happy and excited to find this place. The portions were small. Service and the space were very nice. Mahalo.
(Translated by Google) new discovery  (Original) 新しい発見
Food was really good (sampler plate for $22, but with only 3 pieces of rolled bread). Good amount of food for 2 people - somewhat hungry. Service was good!
Good food small portions

My wife and me were excited when we found out that there is Ethiopian restaurant in Honolulu. I found this restaurant very disappointing for many reasons: The food was not real ethiopian cuisine I know especially injera and Doro Wot that does look or test, small portions  for the price and terrible service. We Ethiopians as part of our culture we share food and use our hands to eat! This restaurant doesn’t provide basic conditions to have clean hands before meal. Handling a restroom key after washing hands is an issue that should be addressed. It is more disappointing that the same issues were posted three years ago and  nothing was addressed. You are Not representing Ethiopian culture “Ethiopian Love” in a good way.
Delicious food! The price point looks a little high, but not worth complaining about when you actually get your hands on the food!
(Translated by Google) A different experience  (Original) una experiencia diferente.
Small portions. Not enough Injera and they make you pay for more. Overpriced. Wish it was different because I’d be here everyday.
Great family atmosphere, corkage fee and BYOB, good food. Family style eating but great experience

Very kind waiter. Attentive. Nice place. Nice ambiance.  Amazing food. Loved the food. The spices and flavors were mesmerizing. I got the veggie platter of 6. Each dish was unique in it's own amazing story of flavors. I would have given a much better rating but they want you to pay for alcohol that you already paid for and brought in. Rediculous considering they recomend you bring your own alcohol since they offer none. This is just wrong since they did not sell us the beverage! It is the reason I wont be comming back. out of principal. Smaller complaints: it was a bit pricey but okay. They also don't provide customer parking.

Ethiopian Love IS ALL ABOUT the love & "Gursha"-Google it or dine there to find out what it means!  The owner Samuel is lovely. When asked why he moved to Hawaii 2 years ago he said "For the temperature and the temperature of the people."  He epitomizes warmth & welcome, and you just KNOW he has a fascinating backstory!
Great food, atmosphere average, service better than average.
Excellent vegetarian sample plate for 2. Enough to feed 4 people Nice ambiance and friendly staff
Super friendly and delicious.
Great food if you're looking for something wholesome and family style. Eat with your hands! That's always fun. The bread is like sour dough so be aware.
Delicious

This was my first time eating Ethiopian food. I didn't  know what to expect and I enjoy trying new ethnic foods.  First of all the initial entrance and dinning area seemed a bit small however we were introduced to the outside area and it was beautiful.  The greenery and water features  were beautiful. Thumbs up all the way.  We started off with the appetizers. And it didn't disappoint. The sambusas were golden brown and delicious. 2 pieces for  $7.50. The food here is indeed pricey and the food is served family style. Prices for food range from 19 to 25 dollars. The flavors were unique and unfamiliar though several of the dishes surprised my with it's flavors. The Ethiopian style iced tea packed a "punch" so to speak. Kind a like punkin pie drink.

I’ve been to this restaurant 3 times so far and I never had a negative experience, food is well prepared and unique and presentation is great, I love you can bring your own drinks, price is fair and service is good
The best customer service and cutes restaurant ever!
OMG!!! So delicious!😋 The atmosphere and decor is wonderful The staff are warm, welcoming and knowledgeable about the cuisine! This is one of my new favorite restaurants!

This place is AWESOME! I stumbled in here accidentally and it has been many years since I have been in Ethiopia. DID NOT DISSAPOINT!  I had the vegan sampler. It's sometimes a challenge to find "healthy" vegan. This was. Highly recommended.  Great atmosphere and friendly staff.
Love

The service was awful. We ordered teas which we never got and our water was not refilled until after we got the check. This was our first time having Ethiopian food and we were not a fan of the spongy bread. The bread was very sour. However if you are a vegetarian this would be a great place to try. We had the veggie platter which was very flavorful. We also had the lamb stew which was not bad.

Food was decent but nothing to write home about; small portions on a large plate is what you get. The waiter was short with us, condescending and unhelpful. Will not be going back nor will I recommend.
Food was amazing. My wife is Vegaj, I'm not. I loved the variety, They have Vegetarian, Vegan and non Vegan options. Hospitality and presentation was great. Be prepared to eat with your hands

So it's a cute small place however the food is the exact same. SMALL PORTIONS!! For a meal that costs over $20 with no sides is a rip off especially for an Ethiopian restaurant. Anyone who has had Real Ethiopian cuisine knows it comes in large portions because the ingredients and process are very humble. Sadly disappointed and the service was poor. Our waitress left for the day before we even recieved our food. They also plated a vegetarian dish with the meat dish and refused to take it back when we had 2 vegans in our group. Will Never Dine Here Again. Top 5 worst places I've ever eaten at. Also all of there drink options were sold out. How do you sell out of tea???

So I wanted to really enjoy this place, as it is the only Ethiopian place in town. And let me say the food is delicious, maybe not the best I've ever had but it's pretty good. No needless to say the loss of stars is from the price and value you get here. Let me explain. We ordered the vegetarian sampler and 3 different meats. For the price you would think it came as a large sample of vegetable dishes and separate meat dishes, but no they put it all on one plate and served a table of 5. And don't get me started on how little injera bread they provide. We had to order bread 3 times to feed us. Overall after 90$ our party of 5 (3 and 2 little children ) we're not full. Overall the value just doesn't really add up here. Ethiopian should be a large meal for a good price. This is a small meal for a huge price. But sadly it's all we have on Oahu...

Everything about Ethiopian Love Restaurant is amazing. From the moment I first walked through the door I felt the comfort of a restaurant I had been in a hundred times. The atmosphere is warm and inviting, the staff is kind and helpful, and the live music tied everything together. But the real star of the show here, is the food. We had the spicy sauteed lamb and homemade cheese and vegetarian sample platter. It was the best thing I have ever eaten in my life. The spices and the aroma are perfect. All of that and the prices are very reasonable. If you have never had Ethiopian food before and you're on the fence, stop what you are doing and go now. You won't regret it.

Positives: Good food very tasty and full of flavor. Place is clean  Negatives: For a place that promotes the use of hands they need to provide better alternative for hand washing. Customers go to an outside bathroom (the waiter gives you a key, which everyone touches with dirty hands then again with clean hands 😝. No paper towel in bathroom to use to open the door after washing hands😩. The service needs a lot of improvement.  I ordered vegan dish ( which is the reason we were here in the first place).  My husband ordered chicken. When our food came they had taken it upon themselves to decide to put our food on the same plate (did not consult us😳). My vegan meal had two (2) pieces of beef in it. When I brought it to the waiter’s attention he seemed reluctant to do anything about it then when he finally told the manager ( maybe owner). She took the pieces of meet to the kitchen and never came back until we were done with our meal. She apologized and offered us tea on the house. We didn’t want any tea. She then said “well I tried”. 🙄🤯 Good food but don’t think I’d be back 🙃. There’s more to running a restaurant than good food. I think the food is too pricy. $17 for mushrooms and two table spoons of beats😂😂
I amazing food and cannot stress how lovely staff
Great food and lovely atmosphere for a quiet date.

If you really crave Ethiopian food, go here (since it's the only one on island I am aware of). Food quality is good. However, super small portions, over priced, and additional enjera cost money (they give not enough, and the refills that you pay for are just small strips of the full enjera). Bad experience overall.
Great food. Great drinks and Great atmosphere.   Loved it!!!
Mostly good food. Pricey, and sting with bread and very bad policy of  forcing customers to purchase more dishes.
Delicious food, awesome staff!

Small, simple place, better than expected food. A bit of a mom and pop feel, probably seats 30 people. Fairly short menu but something for everyone. I had beef tibs and it was some of the best I’ve had. Good portions, reasonable prices.  Service was pretty good. Would return.
Good food less injera but still amazing!

Positives:  - Good iced tea - Good Wot - Good atmosphere  Negatives:  - Terrible service (worst I've ever experienced) - The injera was terrible and too small to eat with - Food took way too long to get served - server forgets and mixes up orders - if you want to get the servers attention you have to leave your seat and walk up to them - they require you to order an entree for every guest seated so be prepared to drop some cash - extra injera costs extra - I can keep going  All you need to know is that this place is not a good representation of quality Ethiopian dining. With service and some food alterations they have the potential to be much better.

If you take away three things: fantastic food; terrible injera; terrible service.  We unfortunately selected this place to celebrate my boyfriend’s graduation (he lived in Ethiopia for 17 years and we love finding Ethiopian food places in Houston where we live). All of us at the table (party of 5) agreed a 1 star rating was quite generous.  This place has a nice atmosphere. It seems to me this would be an excellent experience for a small party (2-4 people) who would like to drink wine and have an appetizer or small plate. We love supporting local Ethiopian communities, but it was a disappointment to both those familiar with Ethiopian food (myself and my boyfriend), and to three first-timers.  It was 50 minutes before we got our food. Our drinks were constantly empty.  The hot tea (Kememe Shai) we asked for never came but was on our bill. We ran out of injera and couldn’t finish our meal. And this place requires, because we had a party of five, that we order five entrees, which can add up.  I’ve had Ethiopian food many times; the injera here is thin and flat and does not have the traditional sponginess or sourdough flavor.  I encourage readers to try Ethiopian food in their local area and learn more about the culture. However, while in Oahu, you may be better served by visiting Rainbow Drive In. :-)

This was something that originally a little out of my original comfort zone but after trying it once I would recommend going again. The food is unique and something way different from what most people eat day to day.
Atmosphere was meh, service was meh, food was good, but the experience as a whole was lacking.
We loved this place. It was very cosy and they have a lovely patio in the back. Make sure you order more of the bread.

We came in a little late, close to close but the staff was still willing to seat us and server still. Which we were extremely thankful for. The food is a communal type dish that you eat with your hands and a special type of bread kinda like a tortilla. It let's you the other dishes at your table and is very good for a second date to get to know someone more. Overall everything was extremely flavorful and cooked to perfection. Would highly recommend this place.

I walked into this restaurant for the first time a few days ago, and didn't know what to expect. My first Ethiopian food experience will never be forgotten! Beautiful people, scrumptious foods, and nobody judges you for eating with your hands!!!  This Hole-n-the-wall restaurant is an iconic addition to anything representing Ethiopian culture on the island!  If you feel like exploring uncharted food boundaries, highly recommend this place  Don't forget to try the peanut tea; it's like hot chocolate, but with peanut butter, instead of chocolate
Love celebrating our 10th Anniversary there with the back courtyard all to ourselves!
So delicious. Great vegetarian options.
Awesome!
Great service. Peanut tea was absolutely delicious. The food was great too
Surprisingly Wonderful!!! Perfect service and beautiful food.
Delicious!
My friend liked it.
Sharing food eaten with your hands is gross...
Awesome food and great service!

They have an unwritten policy that every adult must buy one entree. No splitting or just having apps. Super weird and should really be written on the menu, but aside from that, SO GOOD. Probably best iced tea I’ve ever had.

The service sucks, very unethiopian. Food is overpriced, the thing they call injera doesn't even look or test like injera, they give you very little of it that you have to keep ordering 3 tiny peices for 3 dlrs.

Such a beautiful & quaint little spot. The food was fabulous. Highly recommend the Love Shiro dish and vegetarian sampler dish though I feel like the Love Shiro dish could be bigger, especially for the price. Love Shiro is very tender Lamb slices in a hearty stew. Best lamb I’ve had. I deducted 1 star only because the waitress brought our check when we weren’t even finished and we still wanted to order desert. Then, when we ordered the peanut tea we waited 30 minutes or more and it never came! So we just left without getting to try it. I really wanted to try the tea too as it was highly reviewed. Let me note, it was not busy either so I’m not sure why that happened. Service needs to be better. Otherwise the food is wonderful.

Came with a party of 8. Ordered lots of different dishes...all delicious.  But the lamb dishes were my favorites. The peanut tea is ridiculously good...like drinking liquid peanut butter ....an amazing treat. Baklava a great way to end the evening. I went with locals who love this place. It is inside seating but no a/c so dress cool. Enjoy!
The food and experience were amazing,! If you get the opportunity to eat outside, do it!

This was my first time ever trying Ethiopian food so I'm definitely not anywhere near an authority on the matter of authenticity.... But whatever it was, it was daaamm good! Ambience was very nice and chill. Customer service was great! I got the 1/2 platter or sampler I think it was called. I wish it didn't fill me up so fast so I could have finished it all! Great menu choice for a first timer and a vegan :)
Really good food. But a bit overpriced. And they charge for the injera flatbread. Not cool. Haha. But the food is really good.
Rip off...For my $22 entree, they only gave 3 roll up breads. I asked for more and ‘Ginger’ said $3 extra. Come on!  Your service sucks and the small portions are not worth it. Sorry!
Delicious! FYI for uninformed, you eat with your hands here, so make sure you're friendly!
It was flavorful
Good taste
Was good
Native ethiopians share food. That's the culture. Don't pretend to provide a unique cultural experience and make me order multiple dishes. Plus the food was just aight.
Great food! So nice to to have something different than the ordinary Staff was extremely friendly, with amazing service.
The food is delicious but the parking, the wait, and the price kind of sucks

Ethiopian Love is one of the best restaurants on Oahu! Tucked away on Smith street in Chinatown the restaurant is cozy with lovely decor, attentive servers and amazingly delicious.  Every dish delights. Byob
Food is spiced perfectly, very yummy. Always ask for a fork or spoon if you are not comfortable eating with your hands. Try the Lamb or Beef Stew.

Got there early to avoid a wait and ended up waiting 15 min after the posted opening time for the doors to open and another 15 min for the wait staff to arrive. By then the restaurant was full and our order was taken a total of 45min after the posted open time. We were offered Sambussa by the kitchen staff prior to the arrival of the wait staff. We assumed it was complimentary due to the 30 minutes delay of the staff. It was not. Overall the food was okay and when the staff arrived they were friendly. The prices implied a better overall experience. Try it if you have time and money to burn.
Such a great place. Love the atmosphere. And the food.

Food are really good. All foods came in a large plate for sharing. You eat food with your bare hands so a hand sanitizer might come in handy. I really recommend the peanut tea. It tastes like a warm peanut butter milk. Very smooth.  The reason I deducted one star was because all the drinks came really late. We finished half of the food already before all drinks arrived.

I should note that this review exists wholly on the bizarre service provided by this establishment. Friends recommended that we try out their food since they'd had positive experiences in the past and the joy of sharing plates, as they had done during their last visit. We arrived for dinner and were promptly greeted by staff. We asked if we could be seated outside and our server said we could not as seating was full, offering us a booth. We sat, looked over their options and prepared to order, with each couple (four people total, two couples) choosing a entree to share. We were informed by our server that each individual was required to order an entree. We laughed, he laughed, and then he said that, while his statement sounded like a joke, it was not a joke. We looked around and saw at least four other groups seated and I can confirm that two of the other seated groups were actively sharing entrees. We again asked if he was serious, and our server stated that he was and that we could leave if we were displeased. We even confirmed with our friends about their prior experience was not a mistake. After confirming how high the prices now were per person (I'd guess around $18 per plate) we decided to eat elsewhere.  I've probably eaten at hundreds of restaurants and I've never been told that each adult was required to order a full-sized entree or leave. If that price per plate is acceptable to you and their... unusual policy is not a surprise, then... enjoy... I suppose.
Vegetarian sampler and spicy lamb was amazing. Full of flavors
Excellent Ethiopian food. BYOB.  (But need to order the Kitfo a week in advance.)
Great veggie options , beautiful layout , and lots of flavors. Would visit again !
my go to place for healthy delicious eats.

Even for a meat lover like me this vegetarian place is truly a gem of flavors.  I would give it a 5 if not for the lack of ice in their drinks and slow decision process to accommodate you in their outdoor patio.  It's BYOB with minimal charge for corkage.

Service was awesome but it's just not my pallet... for me everything was one note... savory and sour... with spice...i like having variety... looking for creamy... sweet... spice... savory... crunch... I'm just really picky...
Food was amazing, lots of vegetarian options and great for sharing. Service was iffy but food was worth it. Get the peanut tea for dessert, so good.

The vegetarian platter is worth it's weight in gold. They can make the peanut tea vegan, and it is wonderful after it cools down a bit. Abraham is a very cool and gracious host, and April was sweet enough to sing to my wife for her birthday (and she has incredible vocal talents). One of those places that we recommend to everyone as absolutely one of our favorites in Honolulu.
Place was packed and had to wait awhile for service, but it was worth the wait. They even brought us a few free dishes. Nice people, great food.
Such a cool restaurant. Every plate is sharable which is a little different but but definitely authentic
Very good family style food
Get ready to eat with your hands!  The lamb stew was awesome!  Live music some nights.  Nice outdoor area.

It took forever to get our food and the waitress wasn't friendly. The food was good but I dropped $60 for what was essentially an appetizer and two ice teas. The restaurant was also hot. Worth a try maybe, but I certainly wouldn't go their regularly and definitely wouldn't recommend it on a busy night.
Great food! Slow service
Best Ethiopian restaurant I've been to
Fantastic!

Easy with your hands using the small rolls of tef bread provided. Before sampler was pretty good, as was the lamb and spicy beef Tibs. I wouldn't get any of their daily specials again cause it takes so long to make.
Thought food was a little over priced...

I've never had African food before. Everything tasted great! We had spicy lamb and the Ethiopian Love Sampler. I Love the experience eating without utensils, the bread was perfect. Only prices were more than expected, small kine sticka shock, Africkn dent in our budget.
Food and service were outstanding. Had to pay for parking at a lot down the block, but it's Chinatown so that was expected
Food was absolutely delish!... the service however leaves something to be desired...
The food was delicious but the portion sizes were much smaller than anticipated, more like a large one person serving than a proper family size plate.

Friendly staff and cool old building with a great hidden courtyard. The food was flavorful and fun to eat by fingers with the ijera bread. Had the six vegetable dish for two and we couldn't finish it. Will come back.
Food was good. Had a great time trying out Ethiopian Love. However wasnt wowed overall

Hands down one of Honolulu's best date night spots. Great healthy dinner that even people who don't want healthy will be able to eat and actually get full. It's hearty and delicious and how fun to eat with your hands. So romantic :) I wish you were open for lunch.

Ethiopian food is my absolute favorite. I've had great Ethiopian food in NYC, Seattle, D.C., etc., but my experience here left me looking for the "love." The food and service were fine, but the portions and price were pathetic (worst portions I have ever experienced, especially for the price). Two of us ate two entrees, paid nearly $40, then went to a grocery store so we didn't have to return to our hotel hungry. I won't go back. If you go, I suggest you enjoy the $17 sample plate as an appetizer and then go somewhere else for you meal.

I loved the place. The service was great and friendly. The food was delicious. I had the vegetarian sampler and it was plenty. Live music was playing which just added to the ambiance. Small and quaint place. Definitely a place to visit and become a regular.
This is a hidden gem and I love it! Easy to be vegan here. I've gone for nice dates and big group dinners. Very fun, festive and cultural. BYOB is also a plus.

Wow, our first experience eating Ethiopian food and what a find. Loved everything about it.  Excellent food, good service and reasonable prices. Although we went at a quite time, I am sure it is quite the lively atmosphere with music and entertainment in the evening. Highly recommend it!
The service is consistently friendly, helpful, and attentive. The food is carefully prepared and presented. Everything has been tasty, nothing gets left behind.

My family and I have traveled through out the US extensively. Wherever we go, we try our best to dine in one of the local Ethiopian restaurants. So far our experience has been amazing, leaving the restaurant always proud. However, tonight has been a big disappointment. We were eager to find an Ethiopian Restaurant in Honolulu. We were so excited when we found one online. We decided to spend our Friday night there and went. To our disappointment, the reception was cold and, weird enough, with a musical duo playing a Turkish song. The waitress knew nothing about our food. To begin with, if an Ethiopian Restaurant does not serve Kitfo, it can hardly be Ethiopian Restaurant. And to make things worse, the reason the waitress gave why they could not serve Kitfo made no sense at all. Though the name of the restaurant says "Ethiopian Love " it displayed no love at all. The only apparent Ethiopian guy in the place which we assumed was the owner seemed totally stoned (high) with some kind of drug. He was so high that he did not even extended us the usual Ethiopian greeting. He seemed oblivious to our presence. Anyway, the biggest disappointment was when the food we ordered arrived. Though we ordered three different dishes, the portion that was on our try would only be just one dish had it been in any other place. The price for the taste and volume was a rip off. It was a total waste of our money and most importantly our Friday evening.
GREAT service and VERY TASTY food!
Always good. Better than 95% of Ethiopian Restaurants
Rare but good cuisine in Honolulu
Delicious, authentic Ethiopian dishes, served family style. If you get the samplers only get them for one, for two is almost the same size.
Food used to be good, but not anymore. If you are going to charge me $20 for an entree then you should deliver the quality product.
Great ambiance and a pretty little koi pond out back

Updating this review.  I really like Ethiopian Love now. I actually crave the food and have to get in to town to get it at times. It still has its little quirks so that's the reason for four instead of five stars but the food is GREAT!  The food was good but our service  experience was not. Most notably, I asked for a coffee at the beginning of the meal and I never got it. When the check came it had the coffee that I never got on it and I had to ask them to remove it which they did with no problem. But why was it on there in the first place?
Did not disappoint. Njera is so good.
Amazing food. One of the best ethnic restaurants in Honolulu. Great for groups & byob (nominal corkage fee). Good for vegetarians. Be ready to eat with your hands.
Very good food which sadly comes in relatively small portions and is significantly more expensive than the alternatives in the area.

If you have a vegan/veg partner, but want that umami (meaty/hearty) taste, this is the place to go. The red lintel taste like well seasoned ground beef, and the yellow chickpea mash is just awesome in it as well.  Great place for couples, though be aware going with friends you'll be sharing literal hand fulls of food with each other.  Nice and cozy, and the staff make you feel like grandkids, ensuring everything is good and you get enough to eat.

One of my favorite restaurants on island. Delicious food and a great vegan vegetarian menu. Service is amazing and always kind they treat you like family. Try the telba and the vegetarian sampler plate!

Dined here for the first time with friends. It was my first time eating Ethiopian food so I was pretty excited.  We came on a Saturday evening (5pm reservations).  Luckily, I was able to find metered street parking right outside the restaurant.  I only had to pay for an hour, no charge after 6pm.  There are many lots/garages in the area if street parking is full.  Everything here is meant to be eaten with your hands.  Initially I thought that eating with my hands would be messy but it actually wasn't that bad at all. Everything was easy to grab and eat with the Injera which was a spongy type of Ethiopian bread.  For our appetizer we ordered the sambussas...probably my favorite dish of the night!  We shared the Ethiopian Love Veggie Sampler and 2 meat dishes.  I was very impressed!  The food was delicious! Everything was flavored perfectly! However, the dishes are served with little injera so we had to order more on the side.
The energy in this place is amazing the food is superb and the location is easy to reach
Great Atmosphere, Better Food, Best Restaurant!!!!
Delicious authentic Ethiopian food in a nice atmosphere.
Lovely people, and the food is great. Highly recommend it.

East your food worth your hands.   My favorite restaurant on the island.   Tons of vegan friendly options and may choices.   Food is served on giant dishes with injera so it's great for large groups to share.
Open for lunch on Sunday! Great service and yummy food!
First time eating Ethiopian, it was Delicious. The server was a nice guy, a bit too nice as we didn't expect. Anyway, good food, good vibe, would recommend and have.
We went on a Friday night, wasn't too crowded, great live music & best Ethiopian food I've ever had :]....I highly recommend the Ethiopian Love veggie sampler & peanut tea!
I loved the food and the service was good!
Delicious food!
Very good food, but quite disorganized. Bring your own hand wipes. Nice atmosphere, decor, live music. Easy municipal parking nearby. Artisan ice cream around the corner!
The best Ethiopian food you can find on the west cost!
Every time I have eaten Ethiopian food, I've loved it and Ethiopian Love continues that tradition. The food is great, but the owner's service really is the star.

This place really turns your meal into a mini pizza-ish party. Everything is family style and served on a bread like roll.  The bread is very light, moist and fun to eat.  All of your meats and veggies are resting on top of it. So they do their best to put all of your orders onto one huge dish and you get to pick and choose or mix and match anything you want to go together.  So this is a place that you have to eat with your hands and it can get a little messy at first.  But once you are hands into your meal (the chicken and lamb taste great by the way) you won't remember why you would ever eat with utensils.  Oh and the spicy things are really spicy.

I lived in Bahrain for a year and ate authentic Ethiopian food prolly at least once a week and loved it. This food isn't that, however, to be so far away and in the middle of a place completely over run with every different type of Asian cuisine known to man, this is very welcome and very good. I'm amazed they got it so right. The restaurant was clean the setting was cool. I liked it a lot and will be coming back soon. Well done
This place is amazing and the guys running is very friendly, you will not be disappointed

Went with a group of 6 other people to this restaurant with a friend for her birthday. She loves Ethiopian food and was excited we now had a restaurant in Honolulu. She had made reservations at a particular table in the back of the restaurant, but when we all arrived, we were told to wait in the darkened inner courtyard of the building. After about ten minutes, we asked again about our table. The server, acted as if she'd never seen us before pulled two tiny round tables at the front of the restaurant together for us to sit at, since our "reserved" table or any table of adequate size was unavailable. My husband was dripped on profusely by the air conditioner - We even saw workers mopping up water from the floor nearby. Finally, after another group cleared out, we were able to switch tables. The food was expensive, and the service was terrible. It was so difficult to get service. When we asked for water, we were given luke warm tap water in mismatching cups - In fact, it looked like some of the cups were glass jars that had been used as flower pots. We tried to just enjoy dinner, and the food was good when it got to us. At the end of dinner, all of us insisted on paying for the birthday girl. We were mostly able to pay in cash but not quite. We owed $5 more plus tip, so I put the balance after cash and tip on my credit card. I later discovered two charges from the restaurant on my credit card statement, one for the correct amount, and a second, $75 charge! All I can imagine is that the workers pocketed $75 in cash and charged me a second time for that - I'm disputing the charge now.  Will NEVER go back to this place. What a nightmare!

FACT: Best place for Ethiopian cuisine. I'm shock to find out being the only restaurant and serve the best of the best.  If you are vegetarian like me, this is it. all but the best you will find.  I've actually brought people here about 5 separate times for "1st-time" Ethiopian cuisine experiences. While most were hesitant initially, all left satisfied and pleased with trying something new and delicious  Took out one star for the service, needs improving.

I love this place. The food takes time and the atmosphere is super chill but these are some of the things I love. I have enjoyed Ethiopian food at many restaurants in other places and this one ranks high among them. The Injera portions are a little smaller than other restaurants I've gone to but I think that is because they make it all in house,. Is it delicious and you can always order more. The service is sweet and family like. I always order the vegetarian sampler and I enjoy every dish on the plate it is hard to pick a favorite.
Yummy !
This restaurant is definitely a labor of love for the owners. The food is delicious and the atmosphere is wonderful.
